replyContent: You can transfer the progress from the free version - just go to Settings on the start screen in the old version of the game and click "Save" at the bottom of the screen (to the cloud or locally). After that, in the Ultimate version, click on the corresponding "Load" button in the same place - the game will restart and the progress will be updated.

replyContent: In fact, everything is a little more complicated. After death, you have your XP, gold, gems and recipes, which you can spend on upgrades. And after the construction of the Blacksmith, you can buy items with which you start the next game. And in this game you decide in which dungeon and (under certain conditions) from which floor to start.

It's a good looking pixel art rogue like. The balance is a complete mess 
though. I ended up using ranged classes to beat the game. The melee classes 
end up getting one or two shotted, even when wearing the vest available 
armor. So it feels very unrewarding to play, when you slow yourself down 
with heavy armor but still get immediately killed. In the end, kiting and 
ranged combat felt alot better. Another thing is the restricted use of 
crystals. Only pets are permanent and worthy investment, but you need to do 
it per character. Overall way to restrictive game. Controls are OK, but 
walking, sprinting and attacking can be iffy if you try to cycle between 
them too fast.

Controls are a little wonky but my giant fingers probably don't help, 
otherwise the game is great for its price!

One recommendation if the dev is listening: add a bit more diversity in the way you can use attacks. Let us charge up a sword swing or spell for extra damage, or double-tap to apply an alternate effect to an arrow or summon. Longer dungeon crawls get a bit stale with just three possible moves, so making them a bit more dynamic would freshen things up without taking up screenspace for extra buttons.

There is quite the variety of play styles and stratagems provided via unlock able characters and interchangeable skills. Furthermore, the rate of in game currency (the premium currency of gems) accumulation is much better. The fact that it is earned through daily quests is a favorable option in my opinion. Hours of fun and frustration are to be had with great replay value. This game is definitely worth the initial payment. If you still have progress in the standard version of the game, and in the Ultimate - it does not, you can make a local save.
To do this, open the settings in the standard version (1.16) on the base screen and click on SAVE (LOCAL) on the upper right.
Then go to the same section in the Ultimate-version and press LOAD (LOCAL). This should help.
